# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: png-format
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] In computer graphics, **alpha compositing** or **alpha blending** is the process of combining one image with a background to create the appearance of partial or full transparency.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] It is often useful to render picture elements (pixels) in separate passes or layers and then combine the resulting 2D images into a single, final image called the composite.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Compositing is used extensively in film when combining computer-rendered image elements with live footage.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Alpha blending is also used in 2D computer graphics to put rasterized foreground elements over a background.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] In order to combine the picture elements of the images correctly, it is necessary to keep an associated *matte* for each element in addition to its color.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] This matte layer contains the coverage information—the shape of the geometry being drawn—making it possible to distinguish between parts of the image where something was drawn and parts that are empty.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Although the most basic operation of combining two images is to put one over the other, there are many operations, or blend modes, that are used.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The concept of an alpha channel was introduced by Alvy Ray Smith and Ed Catmull in the late 1970s at the New York Institute of Technology Computer Graphics Lab.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Wallace derived the same straight **over** operator based on a physical reflectance/transmittance model in 1981.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] A 1984 paper by Thomas Porter and Tom Duff introduced premultiplied alpha using a geometrical approach.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The use of the term *alpha* is explained by Smith as follows: "We called it that because of the classic linear interpolation formula $\alpha A+(1-\alpha )B$ that uses the Greek letter $\alpha$ (alpha) to control the amount of interpolation between, in this case, two images A and B".
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] That is, when compositing image A atop image B, the value of $\alpha$ in the formula is taken directly from A's alpha channel.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] In a 2D image a color combination is stored for each picture element (pixel), often a combination of red, green and blue (RGB).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] When alpha compositing is in use, each pixel has an additional numeric value stored in its **alpha channel**, with a value ranging from 0 to 1.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] A value of 0 means that the pixel is fully transparent and the color in the pixel beneath will show through.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] A value of 1 means that the pixel is fully opaque.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] With the existence of an alpha channel, it is possible to express compositing image operations using a *compositing algebra*.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] For example, given two images *A* and *B*, the most common compositing operation is to combine the images so that *A* appears in the foreground and *B* appears in the background.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] This can be expressed as *A* **over** *B*.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The **over** operator is, in effect, the normal painting operation (see Painter's algorithm).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The **in** and **out** operators are the alpha compositing equivalent of clipping.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The two use only the alpha channel of the second image and ignore the color components.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] In addition, **plus** defines additive blending.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] If an alpha channel is used in an image, there are two common representations that are available: straight (unassociated) alpha and premultiplied (associated) alpha.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The most significant advantage of premultiplied alpha is that it allows for correct blending, interpolation, and filtering.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Ordinary interpolation without premultiplied alpha leads to RGB information leaking out of fully transparent (A=0) regions, even though this RGB information is ideally invisible.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] When interpolating or filtering images with abrupt borders between transparent and opaque regions, this can result in borders of colors that were not visible in the original image.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Errors also occur in areas of semitransparency because the RGB components are not correctly weighted, giving incorrectly high weighting to the color of the more transparent (lower alpha) pixels.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Premultiplied alpha may also be used to allow regions of regular alpha blending (e.g. smoke) and regions with additive blending mode (e.g. flame and glitter effects) to be encoded within the same image.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] This is represented by an RGBA triplet that express emission with no occlusion, such as (0.4, 0.3, 0.2, 0.0).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Another advantage of premultiplied alpha is performance; in certain situations, it can reduce the number of multiplication operations (e.g. if the image is used many times during later compositing).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The Porter–Duff operations have a simple form only in premultiplied alpha.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Some rendering pipelines expose a "straight alpha" API surface, but converts them into premultiplied alpha for performance.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] One disadvantage of premultiplied alpha is that it can reduce the available relative precision in the RGB values when using integer or fixed-point representation for the color components.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] This may cause a noticeable loss of quality if the color information is later brightened or if the alpha channel is removed.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] In practice, this is not usually noticeable because during typical composition operations, such as OVER, the influence of the low-precision color information in low-alpha areas on the final output image (after composition) is correspondingly reduced.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] This loss of precision also makes premultiplied images easier to compress using certain compression schemes, as they do not record the color variations hidden inside transparent regions, and can allocate fewer bits to encode low-alpha areas.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The same “limitations” of lower quantisation bit depths such as 8 bit per channel are also present in imagery without alpha, and this argument is problematic as a result.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Assuming that the pixel color is expressed using *straight* (non-premultiplied) RGBA tuples, a pixel value of (0, 0.7, 0, 0.5) implies a pixel that has 70% of the maximum green intensity and 50% opacity.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] If the color were fully green, its RGBA would be (0, 1, 0, 0.5).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] However, if this pixel uses premultiplied alpha, all of the RGB values (0, 0.7, 0) are multiplied, or scaled for occlusion, by the alpha value 0.5, which is appended to yield (0, 0.35, 0, 0.5).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] In this case, the 0.35 value for the G channel actually indicates 70% green emission intensity (with 50% occlusion).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] A pure green emission would be encoded as (0, 0.5, 0, 0.5).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Knowing whether a file uses straight or premultiplied alpha is essential to correctly process or composite it, as a different calculation is required.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Emission with no occlusion cannot be represented in straight alpha.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] No conversion is available in this case.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] The most popular image formats that support the alpha channel are PNG and TIFF.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] GIF supports 1-bit transparency by designating one palette entry as transparent.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Support for alpha channels is present in some video codecs, such as Animation and Apple ProRes 4444 of the QuickTime format, or in the Techsmith multi-format codec.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] This transformation better utilizes the limited number of bits in the encoded image by choosing $\gamma$ that better matches the non-linear human perception of luminance.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] When combined with premultiplied alpha, pre-multiplication is done in linear space, prior to gamma compression.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Note that the alpha channel may or may not undergo gamma-correction, even when the color channels do.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Although used for similar purposes, transparent colors and image masks do not permit the smooth blending of the superimposed image pixels with those of the background (only whole image pixels or whole background pixels allowed).
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] A similar effect can be achieved with a 1-bit alpha channel, as found in the 16-bit RGBA high color mode of the Truevision TGA image file format and related TARGA and AT-Vista/NU-Vista display adapters' high color graphic mode.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] This mode devotes 5 bits for every primary RGB color (15-bit RGB) plus a remaining bit as the "alpha channel".
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Dithering can be used to simulate partial occlusion where only 1-bit alpha is available.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] For some applications, a single alpha channel is not sufficient: a stained-glass window, for instance, requires a separate transparency channel for each RGB channel to model the red, green and blue transparency separately.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] More alpha channels can be added for accurate spectral color filtration applications.
[src:png-format/alpha-compositing] Some order-independent transparency methods replace the **over** operator with a commutative approximation.
[src:png-format/animated-png] The first frame of an APNG file is stored as a normal PNG stream, so most standard PNG decoders are able to display the first frame of an APNG file.
[src:png-format/animated-png] The frame speed data and all of the subsequent frames are stored in extra chunks (as provided for by the original PNG specification).
[src:png-format/animated-png] APNG competed with Multiple-image Network Graphics (MNG), a comprehensive format for bitmapped animations which was created in 2001 by the same team as PNG, which is now obsolete.
[src:png-format/animated-png] APNG's advantages over MNG are its smaller library size and its compatibility with older PNG implementations.
[src:png-format/animated-png] The APNG specification was created in 2004 by Stuart Parmenter and Vladimir Vukićević of the Mozilla Corporation to allow for storing the animations needed for interfaces such as throbbers.
[src:png-format/animated-png] In May 2003, Mozilla had scrapped support for MNG animations, which provides a superset of APNG functionality, citing concerns about the large file size required for the expansive MNG decoder library (300 KB); the APNG decoder, built on the back of the PNG decoder, was a much smaller component.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Among users and maintainers of the PNG and MNG formats, APNG had a lukewarm reception.
[src:png-format/animated-png] In particular, PNG was conceived to be a single-image format.
[src:png-format/animated-png] APNG hides the subsequent frames in PNG ancillary chunks in such a way that APNG-unaware applications would ignore them, but there are otherwise no changes to the format to allow software to distinguish between animated and non-animated images.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Some of the main concerns arising from this were the inability of applications to negotiate for PNG and APNG, or distinguish between PNG and APNG once received, or for legacy software to even inform users that there are additional frames.
[src:png-format/animated-png] The PNG Development Group rejected APNG as an official extension on 20 April 2007, and there have been several subsequent proposals for a simple animated graphics format based on PNG using several different approaches.
[src:png-format/animated-png] The Candidate Recommendation was published on 21 September 2023.
[src:png-format/animated-png] On 24 June 2025 it was finally elevated to the Recommendation final status by the W3C.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Sequence numbers apply to both frame control and frame data chunks, which together follow a common sequence, thus enabling the order and timing of frames to be recovered should an APNG-unaware PNG editor re-order them as allowed by PNG chunk ordering rules.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Frames utilize the same bit depth, color type, compression method, filter method, interlace method, and palette (if any) as the default image.
[src:png-format/animated-png] An application reading a PNG file is meant to ignore any chunks which it does not understand, making APNG backwards compatible.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Applications without support for the APNG extension show only the first frame, disregarding the rest of the frames.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Animated stickers for Signal are APNG with some restrictions (the size of the file is limited to 300kb, the length of the animation is limited to 3 seconds and, visibly (this last point is unclear), the resolution must be 512x512px).
[src:png-format/animated-png] Mozilla Firefox added support for APNG in version 3 trunk builds on 23 March 2007.
[src:png-format/animated-png] However, because libpng is the PNG Group's reference implementation of the official specification, APNG support was not added prior to version 1.8 of the main libpng distribution since it was unratified by the Group before.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Iceweasel 3 supports APNG by using Mozilla's unofficial variant of libpng.
[src:png-format/animated-png] In 2008 WorldDMB adopted APNG as a backward compatible extension to enable animation as part of the MOT SlideShow user application for Digital Radio.
[src:png-format/animated-png] "APNG 1.0 Specification - Animated Portable Network Graphics" is included as normative Annex A in the ETSI standard TS 101 499 V2.2.1.
[src:png-format/animated-png] In 2016, Apple adopted the APNG format as the preferred format for animated stickers in iOS 10 iMessage apps.
[src:png-format/animated-png] On 15 March 2017, APNG support was added to Chromium.
[src:png-format/animated-png] A server-side library exists that allows web browsers that support the canvas tag, but do not support APNG, to display APNGs.
[src:png-format/animated-png] Examples of such browsers include Microsoft Edge Legacy and Internet Explorer 9.
[src:png-format/deflate] In computing, **Deflate** (stylized as **DEFLATE**, and also called **Flate**) is a lossless data compression algorithm that uses a combination of LZ77 and Huffman coding.
[src:png-format/deflate] It was designed by Phil Katz, for version 2 of his PKZIP archiving tool.
[src:png-format/deflate] Deflate was later specified in Request for Comments (RFC) 1951 (1996).
[src:png-format/deflate] Katz also designed the original algorithm used to construct Deflate streams.
[src:png-format/deflate] This algorithm received software patent U.S. patent 5,051,745, assigned to PKWare, Inc.
[src:png-format/deflate] As stated in the RFC document, an algorithm producing Deflate files was widely thought to be implementable in a manner not covered by patents.
[src:png-format/deflate] For example, in the zlib data format, gzip file format, Portable Network Graphics (PNG) image file, ZIP file format for which Katz originally designed it.
[src:png-format/deflate] Deflate compression takes any sequence of bytes and outputs a **sequence of blocks** (commonly called *Deflate stream*).
[src:png-format/deflate] Deflate decompression takes a sequence of blocks and outputs the original sequence of bytes.
[src:png-format/deflate] **Bit 0** is the least significant bit in a byte.
[src:png-format/deflate] Most compressible data will end up being encoded using method `10`, the *dynamic Huffman* encoding, which produces an optimized Huffman tree customized for each block of data individually.
[src:png-format/deflate] Instructions to generate the necessary Huffman tree immediately follow the block header.
[src:png-format/deflate] The static Huffman option is used for short messages, where the fixed saving gained by omitting the tree outweighs the percentage compression loss due to using a non-optimal (thus, not technically Huffman) code.
[src:png-format/deflate] Within compressed blocks, if a duplicate series of bytes is spotted (a repeated string), then a back-reference is inserted, linking to the prior location of that identical string instead.
[src:png-format/deflate] An encoded match to an earlier string consists of an 8-bit length (3–258 bytes) and a 15-bit distance (1–32,768 bytes) to the start of the duplicate.
[src:png-format/deflate] Relative back-references can be made across any number of blocks, as long as the distance appears within the last 32 KiB of uncompressed data decoded (termed the *sliding window*).
[src:png-format/deflate] If the distance is less than the length, the duplicate overlaps itself, indicating repetition.
[src:png-format/deflate] For example, a run of 10 identical bytes can be encoded as one byte, followed by a duplicate of length 9, starting with the prior byte.
[src:png-format/deflate] Searching the preceding text for duplicate substrings is the most computationally expensive part of the Deflate algorithm, and the operation which compression level settings affect.
[src:png-format/deflate] The second compression stage consists of replacing commonly used symbols with shorter representations and less commonly used symbols with longer representations.
[src:png-format/deflate] The method used is Huffman coding which creates an unprefixed tree of non-overlapping intervals, where the length of each sequence is inversely proportional to the logarithm of the probability of that symbol needing to be encoded.
[src:png-format/deflate] The more likely it is that a symbol has to be encoded, the shorter its bit-sequence will be.
[src:png-format/deflate] A match length code will always be followed by a distance code.
[src:png-format/deflate] Based on the distance code read, further "extra" bits may be read in order to produce the final distance.
[src:png-format/deflate] For the match distance symbols 2–29, the number of extra bits can be calculated as $\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor -1$ .
[src:png-format/deflate] The two codes (the 288-symbol length/literal tree and the 32-symbol distance tree) are themselves encoded as canonical Huffman codes by giving the bit length of the code for each symbol.
[src:png-format/deflate] The bit lengths are themselves run-length encoded to produce as compact a representation as possible.
[src:png-format/deflate] As an alternative to including the tree representation, the "static tree" option provides standard fixed Huffman trees.
[src:png-format/deflate] The compressed size using the static trees can be computed using the same statistics (the number of times each symbol appears) as are used to generate the dynamic trees, so it is easy for a compressor to choose whichever is smaller.
[src:png-format/deflate] During the compression stage, it is the *encoder* that chooses the amount of time spent looking for matching strings.
[src:png-format/deflate] The zlib/gzip reference implementation allows the user to select from a sliding scale of likely resulting compression-level vs. speed of encoding.
[src:png-format/deflate] Options range from `0` (do not attempt compression, just store uncompressed) to `9` representing the maximum capability of the reference implementation in zlib/gzip.
[src:png-format/deflate] Other Deflate encoders have been produced, all of which will also produce a compatible bitstream capable of being decompressed by any existing Deflate decoder.
[src:png-format/deflate] Differing implementations will likely produce variations on the final encoded bit-stream produced.
[src:png-format/deflate] The focus with non-zlib versions of an encoder has normally been to produce a more efficiently compressed and smaller encoded stream.
[src:png-format/deflate] Deflate64, specified by PKWARE, is a proprietary variant of Deflate.
[src:png-format/deflate] What has changed is the increase in dictionary size from 32 KB to 64 KB, an extension of the distance codes to 16 bits so that they may address a range of 64 KB, and the length code, which is extended to 16-bit, so that it may define lengths of three to 65,538 bytes.
[src:png-format/deflate] This leads to Deflate64 having a longer compression time, and potentially a slightly higher compression ratio, than Deflate.
[src:png-format/deflate] Several free and/or open source projects support Deflate64, such as 7-Zip, while others, such as zlib, do not, because the procedure is proprietary, and the performance increase over Deflate is small.
[src:png-format/deflate] Implementations of Deflate are freely available in many languages.
[src:png-format/deflate] Apps written in C typically use the zlib library (under the permissive zlib License).
[src:png-format/deflate] Apps in Borland Pascal (and compatible languages) can use paszlib.
[src:png-format/deflate] Apps in C++ can take advantage of the improved Deflate library in 7-Zip.
[src:png-format/deflate] Both Java and .NET framework offer out-of-the-box support for Deflate in their libraries (respectively, `java.util.zip` and System.IO.Compression).
[src:png-format/deflate] Apps in Ada can use Zip-Ada (pure) or ZLib-Ada.
[src:png-format/deflate] AdvanceCOMP uses the higher compression ratio versions of Deflate in 7-Zip, libdeflate, and Zopfli to enable recompression of gzip, PNG, multiple-image Network Graphics (MNG) and ZIP files with the possibility of smaller file sizes than zlib is able to achieve at maximum settings.
[src:png-format/deflate] Inflate is the decoding process that takes a Deflate bitstream for decompression and correctly produces the original full-size data or file.
[src:png-format/deflate] The normal intent with an alternative Inflate implementation is highly optimized decoding speed, or extremely predictable random-access memory (RAM) use for microcontroller embedded systems.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] By operation of the pigeonhole principle, no lossless compression algorithm can shrink the size of all possible data: Some data will get longer by at least one symbol or bit.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Compression algorithms are usually effective for human- and machine-readable documents and cannot shrink the size of random data that contain no redundancy.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression is used in many applications.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For example, it is used in the ZIP file format and in the GNU tool gzip.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] It is also often used as a component within lossy data compression technologies (e.g. lossless mid/side joint stereo preprocessing by MP3 encoders and other lossy audio encoders).
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Lossless compression is used in cases where it is important that the original and the decompressed data be identical, or where deviations from the original data would be unfavourable.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Common examples are executable programs, text documents, and source code.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Some image file formats, like PNG or GIF, use only lossless compression, while others like TIFF and MNG may use either lossless or lossy methods.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Lossless audio formats are most often used for archiving or production purposes, while smaller lossy audio files are typically used on portable players and in other cases where storage space is limited or exact replication of the audio is unnecessary.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The primary encoding algorithms used to produce bit sequences are Huffman coding (also used by the deflate algorithm) and arithmetic coding.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Arithmetic coding achieves compression rates close to the best possible for a particular statistical model, which is given by the information entropy, whereas Huffman compression is simpler and faster but produces poor results for models that deal with symbol probabilities close to 1.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] There are two primary ways of constructing statistical models: in a *static* model, the data is analyzed and a model is constructed, then this model is stored with the compressed data.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] This approach is simple and modular, but has the disadvantage that the model itself can be expensive to store, and also that it forces using a single model for all data being compressed, and so performs poorly on files that contain heterogeneous data.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] *Adaptive* models dynamically update the model as the data is compressed.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Both the encoder and decoder begin with a trivial model, yielding poor compression of initial data, but as they learn more about the data, performance improves.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Most popular types of compression used in practice now use adaptive coders.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Lossless compression methods may be categorized according to the type of data they are designed to compress.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] While, in principle, any general-purpose lossless compression algorithm (*general-purpose* meaning that they can accept any bitstring) can be used on any type of data, many are unable to achieve significant compression on data that are not of the form for which they were designed to compress.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Many of the lossless compression techniques used for text also work reasonably well for indexed-color images.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] These techniques take advantage of the specific characteristics of images such as the common phenomenon of contiguous 2-D areas of similar tones.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Every pixel but the first is replaced by the difference to its left neighbor.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] This leads to small values having a much higher probability than large values.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] This is often also applied to sound files, and can compress files that contain mostly low frequencies and low volumes.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For images, this step can be repeated by taking the difference to the top pixel, and then in videos, the difference to the pixel in the next frame can be taken.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The adaptive encoding uses the probabilities from the previous sample in sound encoding, from the left and upper pixel in image encoding, and additionally from the previous frame in video encoding.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] In the wavelet transformation, the probabilities are also passed through the hierarchy.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Many of these methods are implemented in open-source and proprietary tools, particularly LZW and its variants.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Some algorithms are patented in the United States and other countries and their legal usage requires licensing by the patent holder.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] However, the patents on LZW expired on June 20, 2003.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] As mentioned previously, lossless sound compression is a somewhat specialized area.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Lossless sound compression algorithms can take advantage of the repeating patterns shown by the wave-like nature of the data‍—‍essentially using autoregressive models to predict the "next" value and encoding the (possibly small) difference between the expected value and the actual data.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] If the difference between the predicted and the actual data (called the *error*) tends to be small, then certain difference values (like 0, +1, −1 etc. on sample values) become very frequent, which can be exploited by encoding them in few output bits.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] It is sometimes beneficial to compress only the differences between two versions of a file (or, in video compression, of successive images within a sequence).
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] This is called delta encoding (from the Greek letter Δ, which in mathematics, denotes a difference), but the term is typically only used if both versions are meaningful outside compression and decompression.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For example, while the process of compressing the error in the above-mentioned lossless audio compression scheme could be described as delta encoding from the approximated sound wave to the original sound wave, the approximated version of the sound wave is not meaningful in any other context.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] No lossless compression algorithm can efficiently compress all possible data .
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For this reason, many different algorithms exist that are designed either with a specific type of input data in mind or with specific assumptions about what kinds of redundancy the uncompressed data are likely to contain.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Some of the most common lossless compression algorithms are listed below.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Cryptosystems often compress data (the "plaintext") *before* encryption for added security.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] When properly implemented, compression greatly increases the unicity distance by removing patterns that might facilitate cryptanalysis.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] However, many ordinary lossless compression algorithms produce headers, wrappers, tables, or other predictable output that might instead make cryptanalysis easier.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Thus, cryptosystems must utilize compression algorithms whose output does not contain these predictable patterns.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Genetics compression algorithms (not to be confused with genetic algorithms) are the latest generation of lossless algorithms that compress data (typically sequences of nucleotides) using both conventional compression algorithms and specific algorithms adapted to genetic data.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] In 2012, a team of scientists from Johns Hopkins University published the first genetic compression algorithm that does not rely on external genetic databases for compression.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] HAPZIPPER was tailored for HapMap data and achieves over 20-fold compression (95% reduction in file size), providing 2- to 4-fold better compression much faster than leading general-purpose compression utilities.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Genomic sequence compression algorithms, also known as DNA sequence compressors, explore the fact that DNA sequences have characteristic properties, such as inverted repeats.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The most successful compressors are XM and GeCo.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For eukaryotes XM is slightly better in compression ratio, though for sequences larger than 100 MB its computational requirements are impractical.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Self-extracting executables contain a compressed application and a decompressor.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] When executed, the decompressor transparently decompresses and runs the original application.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] This is especially often used in demo coding, where competitions are held for demos with strict size limits, as small as 1 kilobyte.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] This type of compression is not strictly limited to binary executables, but can also be applied to scripts, such as JavaScript.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Lossless compression algorithms and their implementations are routinely tested in head-to-head benchmarks.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] There are a number of better-known compression benchmarks.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Some benchmarks cover only the data compression ratio, so winners in these benchmarks may be unsuitable for everyday use due to the slow speed of the top performers.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Another drawback of some benchmarks is that their data files are known, so some program writers may optimize their programs for best performance on a particular data set.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The winners on these benchmarks often come from the class of context-mixing compression software.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The Compression Ratings website published a chart summary of the "frontier" in compression ratio and time.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The **Silesia corpus** is a collection of files that was created in 2003 as an alternative for the Canterbury corpus and Calgary corpus, based on concerns about how well these represented modern files.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] It contains various data types, including large text documents, executable files, and databases.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] It is widely used in data compression research.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The corpus consists of 12 files, totaling 211MB.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The files were chosen to represent what the author considered to be data types likely to grow rapidly in size over time, such as computer programs and databases, along with more traditional compression benchmarks, such as large text files.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Because it has a broader and more modern selection of datatypes, it is considered a better source of test data for compression algorithms when compared to the Calgary corpus.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Lossless data compression algorithms cannot guarantee compression for all input data sets.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] In other words, for any lossless data compression algorithm, there will be an input data set that does not get smaller when processed by the algorithm, and for any lossless data compression algorithm that makes at least one file smaller, there will be at least one file that it makes larger.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Most practical compression algorithms provide an "escape" facility that can turn off the normal coding for files that would become longer by being encoded.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] In theory, only a single additional bit is required to tell the decoder that the normal coding has been turned off for the entire input; however, most encoding algorithms use at least one full byte (and typically more than one) for this purpose.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For example, deflate compressed files never need to grow by more than 5 bytes per 65,535 bytes of input.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] In fact, if we consider files of length N, if all files were equally probable, then for any lossless compression that reduces the size of some file, the expected length of a compressed file (averaged over all possible files of length N) must necessarily be *greater* than N.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] So if we know nothing about the properties of the data we are compressing, we might as well not compress it at all.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] A lossless compression algorithm is useful only when we are more likely to compress certain types of files than others; then the algorithm could be designed to compress those types of data better.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Thus, the main lesson from the argument is not that one risks big losses, but merely that one cannot always win.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] To choose an algorithm always means implicitly to select a *subset* of all files that will become usefully shorter.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] This is the theoretical reason why we need to have different compression algorithms for different kinds of files: there cannot be any algorithm that is good for all kinds of data.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Algorithms are generally quite specifically tuned to a particular type of file: for example, lossless audio compression programs do not work well on text files, and vice versa.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] In particular, files of random data cannot be consistently compressed by any conceivable lossless data compression algorithm; indeed, this result is used to *define* the concept of randomness in Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] It is provably impossible to create an algorithm that can losslessly compress any data.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Such an algorithm contradicts fundamental laws of mathematics because, if it existed, it could be applied repeatedly to losslessly reduce any file to length 1.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] On the other hand, it has also been proven that there is no algorithm to determine whether a file is incompressible in the sense of Kolmogorov complexity.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Hence it is possible that any particular file, even if it appears random, may be significantly compressed, even including the size of the decompressor.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] An example is the digits of the mathematical constant *pi*, which appear random but can be generated by a very small program.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] However, even though it cannot be determined whether a particular file is incompressible, a simple theorem about incompressible strings shows that over 99% of files of any given length cannot be compressed by more than one byte (including the size of the decompressor).
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Abstractly, a compression algorithm can be viewed as a function on sequences (normally of octets).
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Compression is successful if the resulting sequence is shorter than the original sequence (and the instructions for the decompression map).
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For a compression algorithm to be lossless, the compression map must form an injection from "plain" to "compressed" bit sequences.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] The pigeonhole principle prohibits a bijection between the collection of sequences of length *N* and any subset of the collection of sequences of length *N*−1.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Therefore, it is not possible to produce a lossless algorithm that reduces the size of every possible input sequence.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Real compression algorithm designers accept that streams of high information entropy cannot be compressed, and accordingly, include facilities for detecting and handling this condition.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] An obvious way of detection is applying a raw compression algorithm and testing if its output is smaller than its input.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] Sometimes, detection is made by heuristics; for example, a compression application may consider files whose names end in ".zip", ".arj" or ".lha" uncompressible without any more sophisticated detection.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] A common way of handling this situation is quoting input, or uncompressible parts of the input in the output, minimizing the compression overhead.
[src:png-format/lossless-compression] For example, the zip data format specifies the 'compression method' of 'Stored' for input files that have been copied into the archive verbatim.
[src:png-format/png] PNG supports palette-based images (with palettes of 24-bit RGB or 32-bit RGBA colors), grayscale images (with or without an alpha channel for transparency), and full-color non-palette-based RGB or RGBA images.
[src:png-format/png] The PNG working group designed the format for transferring images on the Internet, not for professional-quality print graphics; therefore, non-RGB color spaces such as CMYK are not supported.
[src:png-format/png] A PNG file contains a single image in an extensible structure of *chunks*, encoding the basic pixels and other information such as textual comments and integrity checks documented in RFC 2083.
[src:png-format/png] PNG files have the ".png" file extension and the "image/png" MIME media type.
[src:png-format/png] PNG was published as an informational RFC 2083 in March 1997 and as the standard ISO/IEC 15948:2004 in 2004.
[src:png-format/png] The motivation for creating the PNG format was the announcement on 28 December 1994 that implementations of the Graphics Interchange Format (GIF) format would have to pay royalties to Unisys due to their patent of the Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) data compression algorithm used in GIF.
[src:png-format/png] This led to a flurry of criticism from Usenet users.
[src:png-format/png] One of them was Thomas Boutell, who on 4 January 1995 posted a precursory discussion thread on the Usenet newsgroup "comp.graphics" in which he devised a plan for a free alternative to GIF.
[src:png-format/png] Other users in that thread put forth many propositions that would later be part of the final file format.
[src:png-format/png] Oliver Fromme, author of the popular JPEG viewer QPEG, proposed the PING name, eventually becoming PNG, a recursive acronym meaning *PING is not GIF*, and also the .png extension.
[src:png-format/png] Other suggestions later implemented included the deflate compression algorithm and 24-bit color support, the lack of the latter in GIF also motivating the team to create their file format.
[src:png-format/png] The group would become known as the PNG Development Group, and as the discussion rapidly expanded, it later used a mailing list associated with a CompuServe forum.
[src:png-format/png] The full specification of PNG was released under the approval of World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) on 1 October 1996, and later as RFC 2083 on 15 January 1997.
[src:png-format/png] The specification was revised on 31 December 1998 as version 1.1, which addressed technical problems for gamma and color correction.
[src:png-format/png] Version 1.2, released on 11 August 1999, added the iTXt chunk as the specification's only change, and a reformatted version of 1.2 was released as a second edition of the W3C standard on 10 November 2003, and as an International Standard (ISO/IEC 15948:2004) on 3 March 2004.
[src:png-format/png] Although GIF allows for animation, it was initially decided that PNG should be a single-image format.
[src:png-format/png] In 2001, the developers of PNG published the Multiple-image Network Graphics (MNG) format, with support for animation.
[src:png-format/png] MNG achieved moderate application support, but not enough among mainstream web browsers and no usage among web site designers or publishers.
[src:png-format/png] In 2008, certain Mozilla developers published the Animated Portable Network Graphics (APNG) format with similar goals.
[src:png-format/png] APNG is a format that is natively supported by Gecko- and Presto-based web browsers and is also commonly used for thumbnails on Sony's PlayStation Portable system (using the normal PNG file extension).
[src:png-format/png] In 2017, Chromium based browsers adopted APNG support.
[src:png-format/png] In January 2020, Microsoft Edge became Chromium based, thus inheriting support for APNG.
[src:png-format/png] With this all major browsers now support APNG.
[src:png-format/png] The PNG Working Group has been chartered by the W3C, since September 14, 2021, to maintain and develop for the PNG specification.
[src:png-format/png] The third edition of PNG specification, which adds the proper support of APNG, high dynamic range (HDR) and Exif data, was published as the first public working draft on October 25, 2022, and ultimately as a W3C Recommendation on June 24, 2025.
[src:png-format/png] The original PNG specification was authored by an ad hoc group of computer graphics experts and enthusiasts.
[src:png-format/png] Discussions and decisions about the format were conducted by email.
[src:png-format/png] After the header, comes a series of chunks, each of which conveys certain information about the image.
[src:png-format/png] Chunks declare themselves as *critical* or *ancillary*, and a program encountering an ancillary chunk that it does not understand can safely ignore it.
[src:png-format/png] A chunk consists of four parts: length (4 bytes, big-endian), chunk type/name (4 bytes), chunk data (length bytes) and CRC (cyclic redundancy code/checksum; 4 bytes).
[src:png-format/png] The CRC is a network-byte-order CRC-32 computed over the chunk type and chunk data, but not the length.
[src:png-format/png] Chunk types are given a four-letter case sensitive ASCII type/name; compare FourCC.
[src:png-format/png] The case of the different letters in the name (bit 5 of the numeric value of the character) is a bit field that provides the decoder with some information on the nature of chunks it does not recognize.
[src:png-format/png] The case of the first letter indicates whether the chunk is critical or not.
[src:png-format/png] If the first letter is uppercase, the chunk is critical; if not, the chunk is ancillary.
[src:png-format/png] Critical chunks contain information that is necessary to read the file.
[src:png-format/png] If a decoder encounters a critical chunk it does not recognize, it must abort reading the file or supply the user with an appropriate warning.
[src:png-format/png] The case of the second letter indicates whether the chunk is "public" (either in the specification or the registry of special-purpose public chunks) or "private" (not standardized).
[src:png-format/png] Uppercase is public and lowercase is private.
[src:png-format/png] This ensures that public and private chunk names can never conflict with each other (although two private chunk names could conflict).
[src:png-format/png] The third letter must be uppercase to conform to the PNG specification.
[src:png-format/png] Decoders should treat a chunk with a lower-case third letter the same as any other unrecognized chunk.
[src:png-format/png] The case of the fourth letter indicates whether the chunk is safe to copy by editors that do not recognize it.
[src:png-format/png] If lowercase, the chunk may be safely copied regardless of the extent of modifications to the file.
[src:png-format/png] If uppercase, it may only be copied if the modifications have not touched any critical chunks.
[src:png-format/png] A decoder must be able to interpret critical chunks to read and render a PNG file.
[src:png-format/png] Other image attributes that can be stored in PNG files include gamma values, background color, and textual metadata information.
[src:png-format/png] PNG also supports color management through the inclusion of ICC color profiles.
[src:png-format/png] Pixels in PNG images are numbers that may be either indices of sample data in the palette or the sample data itself.
[src:png-format/png] The palette is a separate table contained in the PLTE chunk.
[src:png-format/png] Sample data for a single pixel consists of a tuple of between one and four numbers.
[src:png-format/png] Whether the pixel data represents palette indices or explicit sample values, the numbers are referred to as channels and every number in the image is encoded with an identical format.
[src:png-format/png] The permitted formats encode each number as an unsigned integer value using a fixed number of bits, referred to in the PNG specification as the *bit depth*.
[src:png-format/png] Notice that this is not the same as color depth, which is commonly used to refer to the total number of bits in each pixel, not each channel.
[src:png-format/png] The permitted bit depths are summarized in the table along with the total number of bits used for each pixel.
[src:png-format/png] The number of channels depends on whether the image is grayscale or color and whether it has an alpha channel.
[src:png-format/png] PNG allows the following combinations of channels, called the *color type*.
[src:png-format/png] The color type is specified as an 8-bit value however only the low three bits are used and, even then, only the five combinations listed above are permitted.
[src:png-format/png] With indexed color images, the palette always stores trichromatic colors at a depth of 8 bits per channel (24 bits per palette entry).
[src:png-format/png] Additionally, an optional list of 8-bit alpha values for the palette entries may be included; if not included, or if shorter than the palette, the remaining palette entries are assumed to be opaque.
[src:png-format/png] The palette must not have more entries than the image bit depth allows for, but it may have fewer (for example, if an image with 8-bit pixels only uses 90 colors then it does not need palette entries for all 256 colors).
[src:png-format/png] The palette must contain entries for all the pixel values present in the image.
[src:png-format/png] The standard allows indexed color PNGs to have 1, 2, 4 or 8 bits per pixel; grayscale images with no alpha channel may have 1, 2, 4, 8 or 16 bits per pixel.
[src:png-format/png] Everything else uses a bit depth per channel of either 8 or 16.
[src:png-format/png] The combinations this allows are given in the table above.
[src:png-format/png] The standard requires that decoders can read all supported color formats, but many image editors can only produce a small subset of them.
[src:png-format/png] PNG offers a variety of transparency options.
[src:png-format/png] With true-color and grayscale images either a single pixel value can be declared as transparent or an alpha channel can be added (enabling any percentage of partial transparency to be used).
[src:png-format/png] For paletted images, alpha values can be added to palette entries.
[src:png-format/png] The number of such values stored may be less than the total number of palette entries, in which case the remaining entries are considered fully opaque.
[src:png-format/png] The scanning of pixel values for binary transparency is supposed to be performed before any color reduction to avoid pixels becoming unintentionally transparent.
[src:png-format/png] This is most likely to pose an issue for systems that can decode 16-bits-per-channel images (as is required for compliance with the specification) but only output at 8 bits per channel (the norm for all but the highest end systems).
[src:png-format/png] Alpha *storage* can be "associated" ("premultiplied") or "unassociated", but PNG standardized on "unassociated" ("non-premultiplied") alpha, which means that imagery is not alpha *encoded*; the emissions represented in RGB are not the emissions at the pixel level.
[src:png-format/png] This means that the over operation will multiply the RGB emissions by the alpha, and cannot represent emission and occlusion properly.
[src:png-format/png] PNG uses DEFLATE, a non-patented lossless data compression algorithm involving a combination of LZ77 and Huffman coding.
[src:png-format/png] Permissively licensed DEFLATE implementations, such as zlib, are widely available.
[src:png-format/png] Compared to formats with lossy compression, such as JPEG, choosing higher compression settings can slow processing without significantly reducing file size.
[src:png-format/png] Before DEFLATE is applied, the data is transformed via a prediction method: a single *filter method* is used for the entire image, while for each image line, a *filter type* is chosen to transform the data to make it more efficiently compressible.
[src:png-format/png] The filter type used for a scanline is prepended to the scanline to enable inline decompression.
[src:png-format/png] There is only one filter method in the current PNG specification (denoted method 0), and thus in practice the only choice is which filter type to apply to each line.
[src:png-format/png] For this method, the filter predicts the value of each pixel based on the values of previous neighboring pixels, and subtracts the predicted color of the pixel from the actual value, as in DPCM.
[src:png-format/png] An image line filtered in this way is often more compressible than the raw image line would be, especially if it is similar to the line above, since the differences from prediction will generally be clustered around 0, rather than spread over all possible image values.
[src:png-format/png] This is particularly important in relating separate rows, since DEFLATE has no understanding that an image is a 2D entity, and instead just sees the image data as a stream of bytes.
[src:png-format/png] Filters are applied to byte values, not pixels; pixel values may be one or two bytes, or several values per byte, but never cross byte boundaries.
[src:png-format/png] The Paeth filter is based on an algorithm by Alan W.
[src:png-format/png] Compare to the version of DPCM used in lossless JPEG, and to the discrete wavelet transform using 1 × 2, 2 × 1, or (for the Paeth predictor) 2 × 2 windows and Haar wavelets.
[src:png-format/png] Compression is further improved by choosing filter types adaptively on a line-by-line basis.
[src:png-format/png] This improvement, and a heuristic method of implementing it commonly used by PNG-writing software, were created by Lee Daniel Crocker, who tested the methods on many images during the creation of the format; the choice of filter is a component of file size optimization, as discussed below.
[src:png-format/png] If interlacing is used, each stage of the interlacing is filtered separately, meaning that the image can be progressively rendered as each stage is received; however, interlacing generally makes compression less effective.
[src:png-format/png] PNG offers an optional 2-dimensional, 7-pass interlacing scheme—the Adam7 algorithm.
[src:png-format/png] This is more sophisticated than GIF's 1-dimensional, 4-pass scheme, and allows a clearer low-resolution image to be visible earlier in the transfer, particularly if interpolation algorithms such as bicubic interpolation are used.
[src:png-format/png] However, the 7-pass scheme tends to reduce the data's compressibility more than simpler schemes.
[src:png-format/png] The core PNG format does not support animation.
[src:png-format/png] MNG is an extension to PNG that does; it was designed by members of the PNG Group.
[src:png-format/png] MNG shares PNG's basic structure and chunks, but it is significantly more complex and has a different file signature, which automatically renders it incompatible with standard PNG decoders.
[src:png-format/png] This means that most web browsers and applications either never supported MNG or dropped support for it.
[src:png-format/png] The complexity of MNG led to the proposal of APNG by developers at the Mozilla Foundation.
[src:png-format/png] It is based on PNG, supports animation and is simpler than MNG.
[src:png-format/png] APNG offers fallback to single-image display for PNG decoders that do not support APNG.
[src:png-format/png] Today, the APNG format is supported by all major web browsers.
[src:png-format/png] APNG is supported in Firefox 3.0 and up, Pale Moon (all versions), and Safari 8.0 and up.
[src:png-format/png] Chromium 59.0 added APNG support, followed by Google Chrome.
[src:png-format/png] Opera supported APNG in versions 10–12.1, but support lapsed in version 15 when it switched to the Blink rendering engine; support was re-added in Opera 46 (inherited from Chromium 59).
[src:png-format/png] Microsoft Edge has supported APNG since version 79.0, when it switched to a Chromium-based engine.
[src:png-format/png] The PNG Group decided in April 2007 not to embrace APNG.
[src:png-format/png] Several alternatives were under discussion, including ANG, aNIM/mPNG, "PNG in GIF" and its subset "RGBA in GIF".
[src:png-format/png] However, currently only APNG has widespread support.
[src:png-format/png] With the release of the third edition of the PNG specification in June 2025, now maintained by the PNG working group, APNG is finally incorporated into the specification as an extension.
[src:png-format/png] Displayed in the fashion of hex editors, with on the left side byte values shown in hex format, and on the right side their equivalent characters from ISO-8859-1 with unrecognized and control characters replaced with periods.
[src:png-format/png] Offsets 8 and 9 of the IDAT Chunk represent the required 2-byte header of the zlib data format.
[src:png-format/png] Offset 16 (of the same chunk) represents the 4-byte footer required by the same format.
[src:png-format/png] Additionally the PNG signature and individual chunks are marked with colors.
[src:png-format/png] Note they are easy to identify because of their human readable type names (in this example PNG, IHDR, IDAT, and IEND).
[src:png-format/png] PNG images are less widely supported by older browsers.
[src:png-format/png] In particular, IE6 has limited support for PNG.
[src:png-format/png] Using PNG instead of a high-quality JPEG for such images would result in a large increase in file size with negligible gain in quality.
[src:png-format/png] In comparison, when storing images that contain text, line art, or graphics – images with sharp transitions and large areas of solid color – the PNG format can compress image data more than JPEG can.
[src:png-format/png] Additionally, PNG is lossless, while JPEG produces visual artifacts around high-contrast areas.
[src:png-format/png] (Such artifacts depend on the settings used in the JPG compression; they can be quite noticeable when a low-quality [high-compression] setting is used.) Where an image contains both sharp transitions and photographic parts, a choice must be made between the two effects.
[src:png-format/png] JPEG's lossy compression also suffers from generation loss, where repeatedly decoding and re-encoding an image to save it again causes a loss of information each time, degrading the image.
[src:png-format/png] Because PNG is lossless, it is suitable for storing images to be edited.
[src:png-format/png] While PNG is reasonably efficient when compressing photographic images, there are lossless compression formats designed specifically for photographic images, lossless WebP and Adobe DNG (digital negative) for example.
[src:png-format/png] However these formats are either not widely supported, or are proprietary.
[src:png-format/png] An image can be stored losslessly and converted to JPEG format only for distribution, so that there is no generation loss.
[src:png-format/png] While the PNG specification does not explicitly include a standard for embedding Exif image data from sources such as digital cameras, the preferred method for embedding EXIF data in a PNG is to use the non-critical ancillary chunk label `eXIf`.
[src:png-format/png] Early web browsers did not support PNG images; JPEG and GIF were the main image formats.
[src:png-format/png] JPEG was commonly used when exporting images containing gradients for web pages, because of GIF's limited color depth.
[src:png-format/png] However, JPEG compression causes a gradient to blur slightly.
[src:png-format/png] A PNG format reproduces a gradient as accurately as possible for a given bit depth, while keeping the file size small.
[src:png-format/png] PNG became the optimal choice for small gradient images as web browser support for the format improved.
[src:png-format/png] No images at all are needed to display gradients in modern browsers, as gradients can be created using CSS.
[src:png-format/png] JPEG-LS is an image format by the Joint Photographic Experts Group, though far less widely known and supported than the other lossy JPEG format discussed above.
[src:png-format/png] It is directly comparable with PNG, and has a standard set of test images.
[src:png-format/png] On the Waterloo Repertoire ColorSet, a standard set of test images (unrelated to the JPEG-LS conformance test set), JPEG-LS generally performs better than PNG, by 10–15%, but on some images PNG performs substantially better, on the order of 50–75%.
[src:png-format/png] Thus, if both of these formats are options and file size is an important criterion, they should both be considered, depending on the image.
[src:png-format/png] JPEG XL is another, much improved, lossless or lossy format, that is supported much less, developed to replace lossless formats like PNG.
[src:png-format/png] JPEG XL is more than 50% smaller than JPEG, and that can happen while it's lossless, therefore making it even smaller than PNG.
[src:png-format/png] It also supports high dynamic range, wide colour gamuts, and large colour depths.
[src:png-format/png] JPEG XL is also very efficient at decoding, and provides smooth transitions from the formats it intends to replace, losslessly able to convert from JPEG.
[src:png-format/png] It also excels at compressing without compromising on fidelity.
[src:png-format/png] Tag Image File Format (TIFF) is a format that incorporates an extremely wide range of options.
[src:png-format/png] While this makes TIFF useful as a generic format for interchange between professional image editing applications, it makes adding support for it to applications a much bigger task and so it has little support in applications not concerned with image manipulation (such as web browsers).
[src:png-format/png] The high level of extensibility also means that most applications provide only a subset of possible features, potentially creating user confusion and compatibility issues.
[src:png-format/png] The most common general-purpose, lossless compression algorithm used with TIFF is Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW).
[src:png-format/png] This compression technique, also used in GIF, was covered by patents until 2003.
[src:png-format/png] TIFF also supports the compression algorithm PNG uses (i.e.
[src:png-format/png] Compression Tag 000816 'Adobe-style') with medium usage and support by applications.
[src:png-format/png] TIFF also offers special-purpose lossless compression algorithms like CCITT Group IV, which can compress bilevel images (e.g., faxes or black-and-white text) better than PNG's compression algorithm.
[src:png-format/png] PNG supports non-premultiplied alpha only whereas TIFF also supports "associated" (premultiplied) alpha.
[src:png-format/png] WebP is a format invented by Google that was intended to replace PNG, JPEG, and GIF.
[src:png-format/png] WebP files allow for both lossy and lossless compression, while PNG only allows for lossless compression.
[src:png-format/png] WebP also supports animation, something that only GIF files could previously accomplish.
[src:png-format/png] The main improvements of WebP over PNG, however, are the large reduction in file size and therefore faster loading times when embedded into websites.
[src:png-format/png] Google claims that lossless WebP images are 26% smaller than PNG files.
[src:png-format/png] WebP has received criticism for being incompatible with various image editing programs and social media websites, unlike PNG.
[src:png-format/png] WebP is also not supported across all web browsers, which may require web image hosters to create a fallback image to display to the user, negating the potential storage savings of WebP.
[src:png-format/png] AVIF is an image format developed by the Alliance for Open Media.
[src:png-format/png] AVIF was designed by the foundation to make up for the shortcomings of other image codecs, including PNG, GIF, and WebP.
[src:png-format/png] AVIF is generally smaller in size than both WebP and PNG.
[src:png-format/png] AVIF supports animation while PNG previously did not.
[src:png-format/png] However, like WebP, AVIF is supported across fewer applications than PNG.
[src:png-format/png] The official reference implementation of the PNG format is the programming library *libpng*.
[src:png-format/png] It is published as free software under the terms of a permissive free software license.
[src:png-format/png] Therefore, it is usually found as an important system library in free operating systems.
[src:png-format/png] Some programs bundled with popular operating systems which support PNG include Microsoft's Paint and Apple's Photos/iPhoto and Preview, with the GIMP also often being bundled with popular Linux distributions.
[src:png-format/png] Adobe Fireworks (formerly by Macromedia) uses PNG as its native file format, allowing other image editors and preview utilities to view the flattened image.
[src:png-format/png] However, Fireworks by default also stores metadata for layers, animation, vector data, text and effects.
[src:png-format/png] Such files should not be distributed directly.
[src:png-format/png] Fireworks can instead export the image as an optimized PNG without the extra metadata for use on web pages, etc.
[src:png-format/png] PNG support first appeared in 1997, in Internet Explorer 4.0b1 (32-bit only for NT), and in Netscape 4.04.
[src:png-format/png] Despite calls by the Free Software Foundation and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), tools such as gif2png, and campaigns such as Burn All GIFs, PNG adoption on websites was fairly slow due to late and buggy support in Internet Explorer, particularly regarding transparency.
[src:png-format/png] PNG is the most used image file format on the web since 2018.
[src:png-format/png] PNG compatible browsers include: Apple Safari, Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Opera, Camino, Internet Explorer, Microsoft Edge and many others.
[src:png-format/png] For the complete comparison, see Comparison of web browsers (Image format support).
[src:png-format/png] Especially versions of Internet Explorer (Windows) below 9.0 (released 2011) had numerous problems which prevented it from correctly rendering PNG images.
[src:png-format/png] PNG icons have been supported in most distributions of Linux since at least 1999, in desktop environments such as GNOME.
[src:png-format/png] In 2006, Microsoft Windows support for PNG icons was introduced in Windows Vista.
[src:png-format/png] PNG icons are supported in AmigaOS 4, AROS, macOS, iOS and MorphOS as well.
[src:png-format/png] In addition, Android makes extensive use of PNGs.
[src:png-format/png] Compared to GIF files, a PNG file with the same information (256 colors, no ancillary chunks/metadata), compressed by an effective compressor is normally smaller than a GIF image.
[src:png-format/png] Depending on the file and the compressor, PNG may range from somewhat smaller (10%) to significantly smaller (50%) to somewhat larger (5%), but is rarely significantly larger for large images.
[src:png-format/png] However, some versions of Adobe Photoshop, CorelDRAW and MS Paint provide poor PNG compression, creating the impression that GIF is more efficient.
[src:png-format/png] Color depth can range from 1 to 64 bits per pixel.
[src:png-format/png] PNG supports metadata—this may be useful for editing, but unnecessary for viewing, as on websites.
[src:png-format/png] As each pass of the Adam7 algorithm is separately filtered, this can increase file size.
[src:png-format/png] As a precompression stage, each line is filtered by a predictive filter, which can change from line to line.
[src:png-format/png] As the ultimate DEFLATE step operates on the whole image's filtered data, one cannot optimize this row-by-row; the choice of filter for each row is thus potentially very variable, though heuristics exist.
[src:png-format/png] With additional computation, DEFLATE compressors can produce smaller files.
[src:png-format/png] Interlacing is a trade-off: it dramatically speeds up early rendering of large files (improves latency), but may increase file size (decrease throughput) for little gain, particularly for small files.
[src:png-format/png] Although PNG is a lossless format, PNG encoders can preprocess image data in a lossy fashion to improve PNG compression.
[src:png-format/png] For example, quantizing a truecolor PNG to 256 colors allows the indexed color type to be used for a likely reduction in file size.
[src:png-format/png] Some programs are more efficient than others when saving PNG files, this relates to implementation of the PNG compression used by the program.
[src:png-format/png] Many graphics programs (such as Apple's Preview software) save PNGs with large amounts of metadata and color-correction data that are generally unnecessary for Web viewing.
[src:png-format/png] Unoptimized PNG files from Adobe Fireworks are also notorious for this since they contain options to make the image editable in supported editors.
[src:png-format/png] Also CorelDRAW (at least version 11) sometimes produces PNGs which cannot be opened by Internet Explorer (versions 6–8).
[src:png-format/png] Adobe Photoshop's performance on PNG files has improved in the CS Suite when using the Save For Web feature (which also allows explicit PNG/8 use).
[src:png-format/png] Adobe's Fireworks saves larger PNG files than many programs by default.
[src:png-format/png] This stems from the mechanics of its *Save* format: the images produced by Fireworks' save function include large, private chunks, containing complete layer and vector information.
[src:png-format/png] When saved with the *Export* option, Fireworks' PNGs are competitive with those produced by other image editors, but are no longer editable as anything but flattened bitmaps.
[src:png-format/png] Fireworks is unable to save size-optimized vector-editable PNGs.
[src:png-format/png] Poor compression increases the PNG file size but does not affect the image quality or compatibility of the file with other programs.
[src:png-format/png] When the color depth of a truecolor image is reduced to an 8-bit palette (as in GIF), the resulting image data is typically much smaller.
[src:png-format/png] Thus a truecolor PNG is typically larger than a color-reduced GIF, although PNG could store the color-reduced version as a palettized file of comparable size.
[src:png-format/png] Conversely, some tools, when saving images as PNGs, automatically save them as truecolor, even if the original data use only 8-bit color, thus bloating the file unnecessarily.
[src:png-format/png] Both factors can lead to the misconception that PNG files are larger than equivalent GIF files.
[src:png-format/png] A simple comparison of their features is listed below.
[src:png-format/png] Before `zopflipng` was available, a good way in practice to perform a png optimization is to use a combination of 2 tools in sequence for optimal compression: one which optimizes filters (and removes ancillary chunks), and one which optimizes DEFLATE.
[src:png-format/png] Although pngout offers both, only one type of filter can be specified in a single run, therefore it can be used with a wrapper tool or in combination with pngcrush, acting as a re-deflater, like `advdef`.
[src:png-format/png] For removing ancillary chunks, most PNG optimization tools have the ability to remove all color correction data from PNG files (gamma, white balance, ICC color profile, standard RGB color profile).
[src:png-format/png] This often results in much smaller file sizes.
[src:png-format/png] `pngcrush`, `pngout`, and `zopflipng` all offer options applying one of the filter types 0–4 globally (using the same filter type for all lines) or with a "pseudo filter" (numbered 5), which for each line chooses one of the filter types 0–4 using an adaptive algorithm.
[src:png-format/png] `zopflipng` offers 3 different adaptive method, including a brute-force search that attempts to optimize the filtering.
[src:png-format/png] `pngout` and `zopflipng` provide an option to preserve/reuse the line-by-line filter set present in the input image.
[src:png-format/png] `pngcrush` and `zopflipng` provide options to try different filter strategies in a single run and choose the best.
[src:png-format/png] The freeware command line version of `pngout` doesn't offer this, but the commercial version, `pngoutwin`, does.
[src:png-format/png] Zopfli and the LZMA SDK provide DEFLATE implementations that can produce higher compression ratios than the zlib reference implementation at the cost of performance.
[src:png-format/png] AdvanceCOMP's `advpng` and `advdef` can use either of these libraries to re-compress PNG files.
[src:png-format/png] Additionally, PNGOUT contains its own proprietary DEFLATE implementation.
[src:png-format/png] `advpng` doesn't have an option to apply filters and always uses filter 0 globally (leaving the image data unfiltered); therefore it should not be used where the image benefits significantly from filtering.
[src:png-format/png] By contrast, `advdef` from the same package doesn't deal with PNG structure and acts only as a re-deflater, retaining any existing filter settings.
[src:png-format/png] Since icons intended for Windows Vista and later versions may contain PNG subimages, the optimizations can be applied to them as well.
[src:png-format/png] At least one icon editor, Pixelformer, is able to perform a special optimization pass while saving ICO files, thereby reducing their sizes.
[src:png-format/png] Icons for macOS may also contain PNG subimages, yet there isn't such tool available.
